There was this little boy about 12 years old walking down the sidewalk dragging a flattened frog on a string behind him. He came up to the doorstep of a house of ill repute and knocked on the door.

When the Madam answered it, she saw the little boy and asked what he wanted.

He said, "I want to have sex with one of the women inside. I have the money to buy it, and I'm not leaving until I get it."

The Madam figured, why not, so she told him to come in. Once in, she told him to pick any of the girls he liked.

He asked, "Do any of the girls have any diseases?" Of course the Madam said no. He said, "I heard all the men talking about having to get shots after making love with Amber. THAT'S the girl I want."

Since the little boy was so adamant and had the money to pay for it, the Madam told him to go to the first room on the right. He headed down the hall dragging the squashed frog behind him.

Ten minutes later he came back, still dragging the frog, paid the Madam, and headed out the door.

The Madam stopped him and asked, "Why did you pick the only girl in the place with a disease, instead of one of the others?"

He said, "Well, if you must know, tonight when I get home, my parents are going out to a restaurant to eat, leaving me at home with a baby-sitter. After they leave, my baby-sitter will have sex with me because she just happens to be very fond of cute little boys. She will then get the disease that I just caught. When Mom and Dad get back, Dad will take the baby-sitter home. On the way, he'll jump the baby-sitter's bones, and he'll catch the disease. Then when Dad gets home from the baby-sitter's, he and Mom will go to bed and have sex, and Mom will catch it. In the morning when Dad goes to work, the Milkman will deliver the milk, have a quickie with Mom and catch the disease, and HE'S the son-of-a-bitch who ran over my FROG."

Two Arabs boarded a flight out of London. One took a window seat and the other sat next to him in the middle seat. Just before takeoff, an Israeli sat down in the aisle seat.

After takeoff, the Israeli kicked his shoes off, wiggled his toes and was settling in when the Arab in the window seat said, "I need to get up and get a coke."

Don't get up," said the Israeli, "I'm in the aisle seat; I'll get it for you."

As soon as he left, one of the Arabs picked up the Israeli's shoe and spat in it. When he returned with the coke, the other Arab said, "That looks good, I'd really like one, too." Again, the Israeli obligingly went to fetch it. While he was gone the other Arab picked up his other shoe and spat in it.

When the Israeli returned, they all sat back and enjoyed the flight.

As the plane was landing, the Israeli slipped his feet into his shoes and knew immediately what had happened.

"Why does it have to be this way?" he asked. "How long must this go on? This fighting between our nations? This hatred? This animosity? This spitting in shoes and peeing in cokes?"

My unit's Dr. lady-person gave me some sleeping pills to test out. Basically that if I have side effecst, like say...they tear up my insides and make me wish I were dead or something, it'd be better to find that out here instead of over there. Damn shame is, I got little sleep last night, I'm listening to calming music (Damien Rice), and I took sleeping pills. Forty something odd minutes of laying in bed, nope, still awake. I guess sleeping pills have no effect on me. Lame. Like, uber-lame.

I went to my first military funeral Thursday. After a deployment people are usually allowed a week of non-chargeable leave, meaning it's not counted against there vacation days. This crew chief got into a car accident while home after Iraq. So he survives a war zone, only to get killed while home. That sucks on so many levels.

Anywho, I didn't know this guy so I wasn't sad beyond the, "I feel for his family" type of sadness. But still, the memorial service was heartwrenching. It's probably because I'm enlisted that I find military memorials the saddest. I guess because there's this quiet dignity about them. I don't think I can explain it.

The chilling part is when they had everyone outside and they started playing "Taps." That is such a hauntingly beautiful song. It's always been one of my favorites. Especially in Basic, 'cuz that meant I could go to sleep. But I digress, we were outside standing at attention when you could see the honor gaurd standing with their rifles. Even though you knew what was about to happen you still couldn't help but jump when they fired, and I honestly doubt the reason peopled jumped was just because of the sudden loud noise. There's a huge difference in just hearing a rifle shoot and hearing one fire in a 21-gun salute.

And then "Amazing Grace" on bagpipes is surprisingly beautiful. I hate bagpipes except for that song.


Gah, I hate thinking about death and all that is involved

Dude, I got a ticket today, totally lame. Oh well, I deserved it. I'm just happy I didn't get arrested (how fast I was going is not relevent at this point.)

Anywho, so I call my mom to complain, which if of course standard for me, anywho, she asks me, "So are you going to go that fast again."

Me: No,  this ticket's already going to hurt, I don't know.

Her: Good. That ticket probably saved your life.

Me: ???

Her: I had this terrible feeling this morning that you were going to get killed because you drove too fast. That's why I kept telling you to be careful.

Me: ....



I mean honestly, this whole "not telling me anything until later" is starting to get out of hand.

You Are Emerald Green
Deep and mysterious, it often seems like no one truly gets you. Inside, you are very emotional and moody - though you don't let it show. People usually have a strong reaction to you... profound love or deep hate. But you can even get those who hate you to come around. There's something naturally harmonious about you.
What Color Green Are You?

Man, I am bitching and moaning about today. Ok, so far this week I have been playing "survivor" for some mission with our unit and the Pjs. It's pretty fun. I get to see how things are like on the ground, I get to see some really pretty scenery, and I get to ride up into the helocopter on the hoist.

Except for today. I mean, I got to do all that stuff but it still sucked. Today, part of the scenario was where I had a broken femur and I was bleeding profusly. So I'm laying there, the Pj comes and asks me what's wrong. I tell him, he cuts open my leg, sees the wound (I had a maskthingywhatever) and places his knee on my theigh and puts ALL OF HIS WEIGHT. Now, I was called to pretend it hurt when they touched my leg. I didn't have to pretend. That hurt like bloody hell. 

Oh, it gets worse. They then decide that I need an IV. I hate needles. I hate needles with an undying passion. I hate needles more than... um...your mom. Why? Because they're sharp and pointy. Sharp and pointy and they're used to poke things, because they're sharp and pointy and they poke my skin and...uh...yeah. Anywho,

I start freaking out, see the last paragraph if you want to know why I freak out. But I try to be good. I honestly do. They were going to put it in my right arm, so I clentch my left hand, turn my head away, and I am very cogniscent of my breathing. I take great pains to breath slow and deep. In-out. In-out. In with the butterflies, out with the bees. I am holding on to my sanity by a thread. And then, poke. Next thing I know, I'm getting this tingly sensation all throughout my body. I start to tense up all over. Next thing I hear is "Breath, don't freak out, don't freak out. Ok, he's freaking out. Pull the IV out. Scenerio's over. Call the 60s back in."

So they pull the IV out and I start feeling a little bit better. They sit me up and start asking me questions. Who I am. What day it was. What I was doing etc. I knew it all, but I couldn't talk. My tounge would just not work. I couldn't open or close my hands either. It was like they were asleep, but a hundred times worse. It took about two minutes of struggling to get any movement back in there. Finally, once I could stand but up, I got hoisted back onto the helocopter and went home. My arms are barely not hurting anymore.

Today was fun.

People Envy Your Compassion
You have a kind heart and an unusual empathy for all living creatures. You tend to absorb others' happiness and pain. People envy your compassion, and more importantly, the connections it helps you build. And compassionate as you are, you feel for them.
What Do People Envy About You?

The last thing I need is another obsession. Oh well. Anywho, what I want to start doing is recording my grandparents, for a myriad of reason. For one is they've been around a few more years than I have, and I want to document all of their stories. About how things were when they were growing up, how they met, stuff about their parents and grandparents. I think that'd be cool. Also, they're getting old, and I want to provide a medium to help keep their memory around. I think I'll have fun with this little project.


I had my first fire today. We were starting up the engines when, well...something caught on fire. We put it out, but that helocopter was done for the night, so we had to rush and get another one ready. A tiring experience.

Angel did the math for me and I'm:

1/4 Spanish, 1/4 Choctaw, 1/8 Apache, 1/8 Cherokee, 3/8 black, 1/16 White


And according to my mother, my great great grandfather was an apache indian chief.

I'm royalty: suck on that!


But yeah, my mother's going to write everything down in detail and once I'll get that I'll post it. I am very interested in this kind of thing. I guess it goes along with my history obsession.


Post script: my grandfather on my dad's side's dad was white. His mother: a slave. I wonder how that happened???

I should be home in June. At least that's what I'm going to try for. Robert graduats something and Michelle's getting married. Both within 10 days of eachother, so if I play my cards right, I can go to both. I need a date for the wedding, hopefully Kris can make it somehow.

Friggin, I was going to go to the Fall Out Boy/All American Rejects/Hawthorne Heights concert on Thursday. I had entered it in our system so they wouldn't fly me that night. Fall Out Boy's going to be at the BX for a meet and greet and I was going to get their autograph, not anymore. I have to fly that night. I tried to switch with another gunner, but the problem is, there arent' anymore. I think there's a total of three, counting me, in the squadron right now, and they all need to fly that day. Oh well, such is life, doesn't change the fact that it sucks though.

And as of now, there is no way I am going to Iraq. It's just not going to happen. I mean, they're barely not going to kick me out. But I will be in Afganistan by January.

I flew tonight and I'm not getting kicked out. I did pretty good. I screwed up on some things, but that's going to come with time. I'm still learning and such. (Fucking gun broke on me. And then I had ANOTHER link sep. Fucking gun and etc etc). So not only am I not getting kicked out, I'm cleared hot to fly by myself. And I'm deployable now. Yay me!

Early this evening I had an observation flight, meaning that I just sat in the back and watched. Tonight I will have an ungraded ride. Wednesday night, I will repeat the ride, and it will be graded. And, as one of the head enlisted guys told me this morning in a meeting, "If you do poorly on Wednesday's flight, we're going to start looking into finding Ryan another job. I've already got the commander's approval on this."

Huh.

"Watch 'The Notebook" numerous people told me. "It's such a sweet movie." I heard on more than one occasion. So I did. I went to the store and bought it, assuming it would be a very good movie. And after the first time I saw it, I thought it was pretty good. It was sweet and all that jazz. 

But then I started thinking about it and I realized, that movie sucked. It was awful. It was laughable how they tried to make us sympathize with the main character even though she does not deserve sympathy nor respect. Allie did not deserve sympathy, Lon did. All he tried to do is give everything he mistakenly thought she deserved. And Allie, being the whore she was, goes on and cheats on Lon with an old flame, on the eve of their wedding at that. To say that it just happened is a bold-face lie. As soon as Allie stepped foot on Noah's property the die had been cast. She knew exactly what was going to happen, and she stayed. All blame rests on her shoulders.

After having lied to Lon about her whereabouts, after he catches up with her she's still trying to sweet talk him, make everything seem as if things are normal.


So all in all, "the notebook" was about a girl who whored it up. How sweet.

My life is good. Anywho, it's been a while since I've updated and it's not really my fault. Ok, it's my fault. Wait, no I recant that. It's Angel's and Kristen's fault. A few weeks ago, January 14th to be exact, I, in my infinite wisdom, decided I wanted to reformat my computer. I mean, it can't be that hard, can it? See, it wouldn't have been if I had any idea as to what I was doing. I am one of the most computer illiterate people ever, which is shocking seeing as how I'm a video game dork. Anyways, when I reformated, I got rid of EVERYTHING, which is the point of reformatting, but I somehow forgot to backup my drivers, and appearently without the drivers, nothign would work. No internet, and worse, because all my games requires a graphics card, so I couldn't play my games. I finally got things fixed on the 2nd of February. So that was nearly twenty days of no computer. I had to like, read and such. Oddly, I spent a lot of time sleeping. Anyways, back to why it's Angel's and Kristen's fault. It is there fault because as my friends, they should have known I'm a idiot and would screw it up royally. Therefore, it is their job to protect stuff from me. It's like in the Bible or something. Speaking of the Bible, I have snapped out of my phase, which is good, 'cuz I didn't like being in it. That's all for now. Yay for me being happy! Now all I need is a girlfriend.

I don't know why I'm feeling this way. I know there is a God, I know He loves me. I can't count on the many things that He's done for me and my family, but I can't shake this nagging feeling that I've had for that last couple of weeks. I don't know where it came from. Honestly, I'm not even sure what I'm feeling. I'm not feeling forsaken or unloved, and yet, I know that I'm not as happy as I could be. As I should be. I am a very lucky person. I have good friends. I have a great relationship with my mother. I have a family that absolutly adores me and can't get enough of me while I'm home. But there's something, something stabbing at me in the back of my soul that I can't recognize. Maybe if I knew what it was I could do what's necessary to stop it. Maybe it's my self-confidence, or lack thereof, that I have about me doing my job. Some had said, "You made it through the schoolhouse, you obviously can have what it takes to make it here." But the thing is, I was shocked that I made it through the schoolhouse. I didn't think I would. Hell, I was this close to quitting. Not very many people (meaning no one) knows that. I mean, I actually talked to an instructor about it. Don't get me wrong, I love my job. I just wish I were better at it. It's as if someone turned on a firehose and I'm drowning. For example, someone'll be asking questions and I'll just blank. Then they'll tell me the answer and all I can say is, "Where's you find that at." I don't feel like I'm good enough or smart enough. I've always considered myself intelligent. Not genius or nothing, but fairly smart. High school, when I tried, was easy to me, and yet, not that I'm here, I feel lost and confused. I'm hoping, I'm praying that something will click in me like it did last time and I'll laugh at myself in the future that I ever felt this way. But then we come again about my lack of faith, in which, as I said earlier, I don't know why I'm feeling like that. If only...I don't know.
I put it together all by myself, and it didn't burst into flames, so I'm happy. What's cool is I have matching towels for the blankets (OMG those blankets are so soft).

Hopefully I'll do well, but I don't think I will. Oh well, I'll try my best, get yelled at, and do better on Friday.
